es and social sciences; and, third, accepting that we might actually be stuck with "Latin America," Tenorio-Trillo charts a path forward for the writing and teaching of Latin American history. Accessible and forceful, rich in historical research and specificity, the book offers a distinctive, conceptual history of Latin America and its many connections and intersections of political and intellectual significance. Tenorio-Trillo's book is a masterpiece of interdisciplinary scholarship.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Okt 2019) 4aEuropean history. 4aLatin America. 4aLatino/a history. 4aeducation. 4ahistory. 4ahumanities. 4aintellectual history. 4apolitical philosophy. 70(DE-601)1044703480(DE-588)4125698-0aKultur2gnd 70(DE-601)1063823650(DE-588)4005248-5aBegriff2gnd 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226443232423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226443232.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles